and these are just known points

Yes — those numbers are predefined landmark indices in MediaPipe Face Mesh.

They correspond to specific, fixed points on the face in MediaPipe’s 468-point facial landmark model.

How FaceMesh landmarks work
When FaceMesh detects a face, it predicts 468 landmarks in a fixed order.

Each landmark has an index number:

0
1
2
...
467
Each index always corresponds to the same anatomical location on the face.

For example:

Index	Location
1	nose tip area
33	left eye outer corner
263	right eye outer corner
13	upper lip center
14	lower lip center
61	left mouth corner
291	right mouth corner
So when you write:

mouth_idxs = [13, 14, 61, 291]
you're selecting four known landmarks that are always on the mouth.

What fl.landmark[idx] means
If:

fl = results.multi_face_landmarks[0]
then:

fl.landmark[13]
means:

the 13th landmark on the detected face
which contains:

x
y
z
Example:

fl.landmark[13].x
fl.landmark[13].y
fl.landmark[13].z
Why the indices never change
MediaPipe trains its neural network so that every face always maps to the same landmark layout.

So:

landmark 13 → always upper lip
landmark 61 → always left mouth corner
landmark 291 → always right mouth corner
Even if the face moves, rotates, or scales.

