Yes — in this script lost is the counter for how many consecutive frames had no face/centroid.

Why
lost starts at 0:

lost = 0
If no face is detected (or centroid can’t be computed), you do:

if centroid is None:
    lost += 1
    ...
    continue
So every loop iteration (i.e., every frame read) where centroid is None, lost increments by 1.

When a face is detected again, you reset it:

lost = 0
Important nuance
It’s not total frames lost over the whole run.

It’s a running “streak” of lost frames (consecutive misses).

What counts as “not visible” here?
In your code, centroid becomes None when:

res.multi_face_landmarks is empty/None (no face found), or

in some edge case where you didn’t get points (but with fixed indices, pts will basically always be non-empty if fl exists)

So practically: “face not detected by FaceMesh this frame.”

What happens while lost
While centroid is None:

you command zero speeds (hold): send_speeds(0,0,0)

if lost > MAX_LOST_FRAMES (10), you wipe smoothing history:

prev_smoothed = None
prev_time = None
If you wanted “total lost frames”
You’d add another counter like lost_total that you don’t reset when face returns.


