Yes — you can do this cleanly with a momentary pushbutton on GPIO 6 and remove all keyboard handling.

Wiring (GPIO 6 button)
Easiest + recommended: use the Pi’s internal pull-up
Wire the button between GPIO 6 and GND:

One leg of button → GPIO 6 (BCM 6)

Other leg → GND

Then configure GPIO 6 as an input with an internal pull-up. The pin will read:

HIGH when unpressed

LOW when pressed

✅ No external resistor required if you enable the internal pull-up in software.

Which physical pin is GPIO 6?
On the Raspberry Pi header:

GPIO 6 (BCM 6) = physical pin 31

GND = any ground pin (e.g., physical pin 30, 34, 39, etc.)

So: Pin 31 ↔ button ↔ GND.

Debouncing
Real buttons “bounce” and can register multiple presses. You handle that in software with either:

a debounce time (simple), or

edge detection callbacks (cleanest)

I’ll show you a simple approach that works well.

Code changes (remove keyboard stuff, add GPIO 6 button)
